A '''spiritual bypass''' or '''spiritual bypassing''' is a "tendency to use spiritual ideas and practices to sidestep or avoid facing unresolved emotional issues, psychological wounds, and unfinished developmental tasks".{{sfn|Fossella|Welwood|2011}} The term was introduced in the early 1980s by [[John Welwood]], a Buddhist teacher and psychotherapist.{{sfn|Fossella|Welwood|2011}}{{sfn|Welwood|2000}}{{sfn|Masís|2002}} Spiritual bypass can be addressed with various forms of [[psychotherapy]], including [[Focusing (psychotherapy)|focusing]] and [[motivational interviewing]].{{sfn|Welwood|2000}}{{sfn|Clarke|Giordano|Cashwell|Lewis|2013}}

==In neo-Advaita==
{{Primary sources|section|date=July 2016}}
Some [[neo-Advaita]] teachers, such as [[Jeff Foster (spiritual teacher)|Jeff Foster]]{{sfn|Foster|2011}} and [[Andrew Cohen (spiritual teacher)|Andrew Cohen]],{{sfn|Cohen|2015}} have admitted that their own insight or "awakening" did not put an end to being a human being with personal, and even egoistical, feelings, aspirations and fears. Although he did not use the term "spiritual bypass", Cohen admitted that his "misguided efforts to create breakthroughs" caused "much harm" to some of his students.{{sfn|Cohen|2015}}

